  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/\r\n-->\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nWe've seen scalability issues with the current aws-ebs volume provisioner impl, which is querying possible zones from cloud provider directly (#76975). The improvement proposed in #76976 did make api calls more efficient, but also raises people's concern about whether it will create regression or not, or is there any more reliable ways to improve.\r\n\r\nTo summarize, there are 2 major concerns:\r\n\r\n1. Is zone info in Node label trustworthy?\r\nMy answer is **yes**, since currently the zone labels (beta version only) are maintained by node controller, the information is retrieved from cloud provider directly and is always updated during node reconciliation, it can be trusted. Even if kubelet can be misconfigured by wrong zone information, node controller is going to override them.\r\nSee: https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/pkg/controller/cloud/node_controller.go#L222\r\nOnce we have the GA version of zone labels pushed out, we should update node controller to maintain both zone labels. It's fair enough to assume that if user wants kubelet to report zone/region, the information should be correct.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. Are the master/minion labels trustworthy?\r\nMy answer is **\"semantic wide they are equivalent to checking node labels from cloud provider\"** - just as people are not required to set master/minion labels in v1.Node, well-known labels in cloud provider is not guaranteed to be set as well. Therefore besides mainstream cluster provisioners, which maintains these sets of labels in both Kubernetes and cloud provider, the function's behavior will remain unchanged: the original impl skips nodes that are **explicitly labeled** with well-known master labels, same here.\r\n\r\nPlease suggest.\r\n\r\n/sig aws\r\n/sig cloud-provider\r\n/kind bug\r\n/priority important-soon\r\n\r\n/cc @liggitt @smarterclayton @mcrute @micahhausler @jsafrane @justinsb \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
